Within the jousting scene it was common to refer to strikes by which area of an opponent’s shield they were aimed towards. Striking towards Pale Chief, Pale Fess, or the opponent's helm were considered aggressive strikes that limited posture and seating position, leaving one vulnerable to strikes. All other strikes were considered defensive and allowed for changing one's posture with ease.

===Equipment===
Equipment included [[Lance#Varieties_of_Lances|jousting lances]], which were lances specially designed to lessen injuries, Individual knights were often identified by colorful patterned dress, heraldry, or banners, as well as matching [[caparison]]s for their mount.

Alternatively, if a jousting lance was too expensive for a rider to acquire they might opt for a '''lance cup''', which were blunted caps of wood fitted over lances to make them suitable for tournament use. However, lance cups were notoriously undependable, having a chance to detach and fall off the lance they were on. Whenever this occurred a joust's officials would interrupt, having contestants start over, and if this were to repeatedly occur it could garner the risk of disqualification.<ref>

document_data.Reputation:
Jousting was a common sport all over [[Faerûn]], with some noted areas of practice including the [[Border Kingdoms]], [[Tethyr]],{{Cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2008)/12-05 - Horse Riding in the Realms}} the [[Dalelands]],{{Cite polyhedron/130/City Stories|15}} [[Sespech]], [[Waterdeep]],{{Cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2005)/01-05 - Festivals of Brightswords, Fists, and Misrule}}{{Cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2008)/12-05 - Horse Riding in the Realms}}

In Sespech, the three-day festival known as the [[Feast of Purple Majesty]] held jousting matches on its first day, the Dawn of Equines.

In Cormyr and Sembia, jousting competitions were a traditional feature of the festival of [[Fists]].{{Cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2005)/01-05 - Festivals of Brightswords, Fists, and Misrule}} Within the kingdom of Cormyr, the first three points of any jousting match were denoted by flags depicting the Cormyrean seal, with a fourth flag reserved for only the winner of a tie-breaker. Cormyrean tournaments also had jousting manuals for sale at stalls and certain color schemes reserved for Cormyrean noble houses.

In [[Chult]], [[Fort Beluarian]] held monthly jousting tournaments.<ref>

Outside the walls of [[Ravens Bluff]], annual jousting events were held by [[Chauntean]] [[cleric]]s on [[Tarsakh 4]] as part of the celebration known as [[the Arming]].{{Cite polyhedron/130/City Stories|15}} The city was also host to jousting contests during its [[Ravens Bluff Town Fair|Town Fair]].<ref>{{Cite polyhedron/109/The Ravens Bluff Trumpeter}}

In the city of Waterdeep, horseback and griffon-back jousts were held in the [[Field of Triumph]].{{Cite adventurers league/Chaos in the City of Splendors|17}}

The lesser sanctuary of the [[Silver Halls]], a [[Tyrran]] temple, had tapestries depicting scenes of conflict and jousting.<ref>{{Cite polyhedron/128/City Stories|11}} And the Tyyran order [[Knights of Samular]] regularly practiced the art of jousting at [[Summit Hall]].<ref>

Beyond Faerûn, in the [[Endless Wastes]], [[Hubadai Khahan]] and his traveling court [[Queraband]] held jousting matches at their annual spring festivals in the [[Valley of the God]].{{Cite web enhancement/The Horde: Barbarians of the Endless Waste|9}}

Beyond the [[Prime Material]], the [[marid]]s of the [[Citadel of Ten Thousand Pearls]] often held jousting matches.<ref>
